\paragraph{Context}
The theorem concerns the characteristic polynomial of an $n\times n$ doubly companion matrix $X$, defined in terms of two given polynomials $\alpha(z)$ and $\beta(z)$ of degree $n$. The matrix $X$ is constructed from the coefficients $\alpha_i$ and $\beta_i$ as shown in (550a).

Variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $n$: dimension of the matrix $X$, a positive integer
    \item $X$: $n \times n$ doubly companion matrix defined in (550a)
    \item $\alpha(z)$: polynomial $\alpha(z) = 1 + \alpha_1 z + \cdots + \alpha_n z^n$
    \item $\beta(z)$: polynomial $\beta(z) = 1 + \beta_1 z + \cdots + \beta_n z^n$
    \item $\alpha_i$: coefficients of $\alpha(z)$, for $i = 1,\dots,n$
    \item $\beta_i$: coefficients of $\beta(z)$, for $i = 1,\dots,n$
\end{itemize}

Referenced equations:
\begin{equation}\label{550a}
X = \begin{bmatrix}
-\alpha_1 & -\alpha_2 & \cdots & -\alpha_{n-1} & -\alpha_n - \beta_n \\
1 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & -\beta_{n-1} \\
0 & 1 & \cdots & 0 & -\beta_{n-2} \\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots \\
0 & 0 & \cdots & 1 & -\beta_1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
